st neighbor of neighbors) {\n      visit(neighbor);\n    }\n    visiting.delete(node);\n    visited.add(node);\n    result.push(node);\n  }\n\n  for (const node of graph.keys()) {\n    if (!visited.has(node)) {\n      visit(node);\n    }\n  }\n\n  return result.reverse();\n}\n\nexport { toposort, CycleError, Graph };\n```\n\nI'm using a recursive DFS approach with a visiting set to track nodes currently in the recursion stack—if I encounter a node that's already visiting, that indicates a cycle. After processing all neighbors, I mark the node as visited and add it to the result, then reverse at the end to get the correct topological order.\n\nFor exports, the spec implies I need `toposort` as the main function, `CycleError` for cycle detection, and `Graph` as the type representation. Since no test examples are provided, I'm inferring the API from the requirements. I should make this generic to handle any node type rather than restricting to specific types. The error handling should use standard Error subclasses rather than Effect-based failures.\n\nHere's my implementation: a `CycleError` class extending Error, a generic `Graph<T>` type using Map and Set, and a `toposort` function that performs DFS with cycle detection by tracking visited and currently-visiting nodes. When a node is encountered while still in the visiting set, that indicates a cycle. The function processes all nodes, reverses the result to get the correct topological order, and exports all three components.",
